Utils Functions

In [2]:
#This Function get two dataset as input, one - of feature to impute by KNN, second - of feature not to impute.
#the output is an integrated dataset, contains both datasets after KNN impution.
def knn_imput(to_impute,not_for_impute):
    knn_df = to_impute.copy(deep=True)

    # use KNN to impute missing values
    imputer = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=5, weights="distance")
    imputed = imputer.fit_transform(knn_df)

    # replace values in the dataset with new imputed values
    knn_df[knn_df.columns] = imputed
    #merge the imputed dataset with the stations and dates dataset
    imputed_joined_df = pd.concat([not_for_impute, knn_df] , axis=1)
    return imputed_joined_df
In [3]:
#This function get a dataframe as input, runs k-means with some different values of number of clusters,
# and show plot of general variance for each run with different cluster number
def elbow_met(df):

    # k means determine k
    distortions = []
    K = range(1,10)
    for k in K:
        kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(df)
        kmeanModel.fit(df)
        distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df.shape[0])

    # Plot the elbow
    plt.plot(K, distortions, 'bx-')
    plt.xlabel('k')
    plt.ylabel('Within groups sum of squares')
    plt.title('The Elbow Method showing the optimal k')
    plt.show()
In [4]:
#This function gets a year and return the matched eligible_voters column from the grouped merged section c df
def return_column_name(year):
    if year == 2002:
        return 'eligible_voters_2002'
    if year == 2004:
        return 'eligible_voters_2004'
    if year == 2006:
        return 'eligible_voters_2006'
    if year == 2008:
        return 'eligible_voters_2008'
    if year == 2010:
        return 'eligible_voters_2010'
    return 'eligible_voters_2012'
In [5]:
# This function get dataframe and list of feature names that we need to impute.
# The output is the same dataset after imputation
def encoding_features(df,feat_to_encod_list):
    # get categorical variables after dropping observations
    categorical_features = df[feat_to_encod_list]
    # one-hot encoding
    encoded = pd.get_dummies(categorical_features, drop_first=True)
    # drop categorical variables
    df.drop(feat_to_encod_list, axis=1, inplace=True)
    # add new encoded variables to the dataframe
    return pd.concat([df, encoded], axis=1)
In [6]:
#this function get ml model and train data and print plot of importance for each feature and return a feature importance df
def feat_importance(grid_search, train_x, train_y):
    # get feature importance
    imp = pd.DataFrame(grid_search.best_estimator_.fit(train_x, train_y).feature_importances_,
                       index=train_x.columns, columns=['Importance']).sort_values('Importance')
    greater_then_0 = imp.loc[imp['Importance'] > 0.002]
    # plot feature importance
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    plt.barh(range(0, len(greater_then_0)), greater_then_0['Importance'], color='#9ecae1')
    plt.grid(axis='x', alpha=0.5, color='lightgrey')
    plt.yticks(range(0, len(greater_then_0)), greater_then_0.index)
    plt.title('Feature Importance', fontsize=14)
    plt.show()
    return imp
In [7]:
#this function return a list of most important features for a given  model features important dataframe(imp)
def important_feaures(imp):
    feat_list = reversed(imp.index)
    impo_feats = list()
    for feat_impo in feat_list:
        if imp.loc[imp.index == feat_impo].values[0][0] > 0:
            impo_feats.append(feat_impo)
    return impo_feats
In [8]:
#return exp with base e of a given number
def exp(num):

    #because we used log transformation on our train data this is possible to get an not a whole prediction for the #sale, we rounded the result in order to get a valid prediction

    if num > 0:#if num > 0(if we would try to return e^0 we will receive 1 and that an error )
        return round(e**num)
    return 0#if num is 0
In [9]:
# define function to calculate metrics
def get_metrics(grid_search,y_test, y_pred):

    actual_pos = y_test == 0
    actual_neg = y_test == 1
    #get confusion matrix
    mat = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    tp, fn, fp, tn = mat.ravel()
    #calculate sensitivity and specificity
    eval_Df = {"sensitivity": tp/(tp+fn), "specificity": tn/(tn+fp)}
    pd.DataFrame(data=eval_Df, index=[0])

    return tp/(tp+fn), tn/(tn+fp)

Creating model for prediction of sample state

In order to determine which features are the best for seperating the states,
we will create a Classification model to predict the county's state
The 8 feauters with the highest feature importance rank will be chosen for the clustering.

In [51]:
#split to x and y
X_cls = section_b_df.drop(['State','FIPS','County','fips_x','fips_y'],axis=1,inplace=False)
y_cls = section_b_df['State']
In [52]:
# Split dataset into training set and test set
X_cls_train, X_cls_test, y_cls_train, y_cls_test = train_test_split(X_cls, y_cls, test_size=0.3, random_state=RSEED)

Classificetion tree

In [53]:
##sclearn implementation
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=RSEED)
# define parameter grid
parameters_grid = {
    'max_depth': [2,4,5,6,7],
    'min_samples_leaf': [2,4,6,8],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 4, 8],
}

# define grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt, param_grid=parameters_grid, cv=10)

# fit estimator
start_time = time.time()
grid_search.fit(X_cls_train, y_cls_train)
print("building classify tree ended in %s seconds" % (time.time() - start_time))
# get best estimator
best = grid_search.best_estimator_

# print best parameters
print(pd.DataFrame.from_dict(grid_search.best_params_, orient='index', columns=['Selected Value']).T)
# predict
y_pred = best.predict(X_cls_test)

#evaluating
# calculate accuracy
acc = round(accuracy_score(y_cls_test, y_pred), 3)

df = pd.DataFrame([acc]).T
df = df.rename(index={0: 'Decision Tree Classifier'}, columns={0: 'Accuracy'})
df
print(df)

#confusion_matrix
plot_confusion_matrix(grid_search, X_cls_test, y_cls_test)
plt.show()

                          Accuracy

Performing standardization

Because most of the Dimension reduction algorithms are based on among other things on Euclidean distance
we will perform standardization on our features to prevent from one feature to have more impact unwillingly.

study limitations

In section c we were asked to build a model whose training is 8 years prior to the test (2012, 2010).

A turnout in a particular district can be calculated as follows: totalvotes in the district (in a given year) / pop (population size in the district in that year) - age_under_18 (in the district in that year).

That is: the number of actual voters / the number of eligible voters.

The problem is that the relevant given population size is only for the years 2010, 2012. In addition, the relevant age_under_18 figure given to us is only for 2010.

Therefore in order to calculate the turnout we must create the following values ​​for each district in the relevant years of the training database: General population size Percentage of people under the age of 18

To this end, we will estimate the change in the size of the population in the years 2010-2017, and make an average of the percentage change. Finally, we will contain the percentage of change cumulatively from 2000 to 2010.

We will also use the percentage of people under the age of 18 as a regular for all years in a training date.

Missing data the could have made estimate more accurate: pop(2002-2008), age_under_18(2002-2008,2012)

general_demog_df_sec_c = demog_df.copy(deep=True)

#average population change in 2010-2017
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(pop_groth_per=lambda x: (x['pop2011']/ x['pop2010'] +                                                                                     x['pop2012']/ x['pop2011']
                                                                                + x['pop2013']/ x['pop2012'] + x['pop2014']/ x['pop2013']
                                                                               + x['pop2015']/ x['pop2014'] + x['pop2016']/ x['pop2015'] + x['pop2017']/ x['pop2016'] ) / 7 )

#estimate population
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(pop2002=lambda x: x['pop2000']* x['pop_groth_per']**2)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(pop2004=lambda x: x['pop2002']* x['pop_groth_per']**2)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(pop2006=lambda x: x['pop2004']* x['pop_groth_per']**2)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(pop2008=lambda x: x['pop2006']* x['pop_groth_per']**2)

#estimate eligible voters
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(eligible_voters_2002=lambda x: (x['pop2002'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(eligible_voters_2004=lambda x: (x['pop2004'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(eligible_voters_2006=lambda x: (x['pop2006'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(eligible_voters_2008=lambda x: (x['pop2008'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(eligible_voters_2010=lambda x: (x['pop2010'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_c = general_demog_df_sec_c.assign(eligible_voters_2012=lambda x: (x['pop2012'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)

#selecting relevant features for estimating eligible_voters
section_c_df = general_demog_df_sec_c[['fips','state', 'eligible_voters_2002', 'eligible_voters_2004', 'eligible_voters_2006', 'eligible_voters_2008', 'eligible_voters_2010',
                                       'eligible_voters_2012']]
#grouping counties by state
section_c_df_groupedby = section_c_df.groupby(['state'])

section_c_df_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#estimating eligible_voters for 2002-2012
for key,item in section_c_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state = section_c_df_groupedby.get_group(key)
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2002'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2002'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2004'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2004'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2006'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2006'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2008'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2008'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2010'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2010'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2012'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2012'].sum()
    section_c_df_after_arrange = section_c_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state.iloc[0:1,1:])

In [82]:
#grouping counties by state and year
house_section_c_df_groupedby = merged_section_C.groupby(['state','year'])

house_section_c_df_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#estimating vote turnouts and D/R class for each state for 2002-2012
for key,item in house_section_c_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state_per_year = item
    #getting the matched eligible_voters column name
    column_name = return_column_name(key[1])

    #calc vote turnout
    counties_per_state_per_year['vote_turnouts'] = counties_per_state_per_year['candidatevotes'].sum()/counties_per_state_per_year[column_name].iloc[:1].values[0]

    #calc Republican votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party'] == 'REPUBLICAN']['candidatevotes'].sum()
    #calc Democrats votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party'] == 'DEMOCRAT']['candidatevotes'].sum()

    # classify state as D or R based on total votes of each party
    if counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0] >= counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0]:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party'] = 'D'
    else:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party'] = 'R'

    num_of_counties = len(counties_per_state_per_year)
    #calc the amount of special = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['special'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['special'] == 1]['special'])/num_of_counties
    #calc the amount of writein = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] == 1]['writein'])/num_of_counties

    #add row to the arranged df
    house_section_c_df_after_arrange = house_section_c_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state_per_year.iloc[0:1,:])

Checking votes turnouts Distribution

As we know if our target feature(vote_turnouts) data is very positive skewed that will cause problem to
regression models, because they will be trained mostly on averaged or small data, and won't be able to
predict properly higher vote_turnouts. The same problem happen when the data is very negative skewed.
There for we will check votes turnouts distribution.

In [87]:
sns.displot(data=house_section_c_df_after_arrange.loc[:,'vote_turnouts'])
sns.displot(data=house_section_c_df_after_arrange.loc[:,'vote_turnouts'], kind="kde")
Out[87]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x194c0905610>

As we can see the distribution is close to symmetric, so we won't have to apply normalization method on the data.

Checking for outliers

Outliers can have bad influence on the results of a regression model because they highly effect
Statistical indices like the mean, that is used to estimate predictions
in many supervised ML models.
Therefor lets print a boxplot and see if there are any outliers in the data.
those outliers, if exist can be recognize as data points beyond Q1-1.5*IQR or Q3+1.5*IQR.

In [88]:
# To deal with outliers, we will need to find them.
# Let's look at the data in the box plot.
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
ax = sns.boxplot(x=house_section_c_df_after_arrange['vote_turnouts'])

#grouping counties by state and year
merged_president_df_groupedby = merged_president_df.groupby(['state','year'])

merged_president_df_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#estimating vote turnouts and D/R class for each state for 2002-2012
for key,item in merged_president_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state_per_year = item
    #getting the matched eligible_voters column name
    column_name = return_column_name(key[1])

    #calc vote turnout
    counties_per_state_per_year['vote_turnouts'] = counties_per_state_per_year['candidatevotes'].sum()/counties_per_state_per_year[column_name].iloc[:1].values[0]

    #calc Republican votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'REPUBLICAN']['candidatevotes'].sum()
    #calc Democrats votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'DEMOCRAT']['candidatevotes'].sum()

    # classify state as D or R based on total votes of each party
    if counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0] >= counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0]:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] = 'D'
    else:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] = 'R'

    num_of_counties = len(counties_per_state_per_year)
    #calc the amount of writein = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] == 1]['writein'])/num_of_counties

    #add row to the arranged df
    merged_president_df_after_arrange = merged_president_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state_per_year.iloc[0:1,:])

Estimating votes turnouts for the presidential elections and determine the majority party for each state.

In [120]:
#grouping counties by state and year
merged_senate_df_groupedby = merged_senate_df.groupby(['state','year'])

merged_senate_df_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#estimating vote turnouts and D/R class for each state for 2002-2012
for key,item in merged_senate_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state_per_year = item
    #getting the matched eligible_voters column name
    column_name = return_column_name(key[1])

    #calc vote turnout
    counties_per_state_per_year['vote_turnouts'] = counties_per_state_per_year['candidatevotes'].sum()/counties_per_state_per_year[column_name].iloc[:1].values[0]

    #calc Republican votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'REPUBLICAN']['candidatevotes'].sum()
    #calc Democrats votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'DEMOCRAT']['candidatevotes'].sum()

    # classify state as D or R based on total votes of each party
    if counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0] >= counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0]:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] = 'D'
    else:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] = 'R'

    num_of_counties = len(counties_per_state_per_year)
    #calc the amount of writein = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] == 1]['writein'])/num_of_counties
    #calc the amount of special = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['special'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['special'] == 1]['special'])/num_of_counties

    #add row to the arranged df
    merged_senate_df_after_arrange = merged_senate_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state_per_year.iloc[0:1,:])

Train Test split

Train = 2002 -> 2008
Test = 2010, 2012

In [134]:
sect_c_train = section_c_finale_df.loc[(section_c_finale_df['year'] >=2002) & (section_c_finale_df['year'] <= 2008) ]
sect_c_test = section_c_finale_df.loc[(section_c_finale_df['year'] >=2010) & (section_c_finale_df['year'] <= 2012) ]

X, Y split

Y = vote turnouts of house election, called vote_turnouts in the dataframe.
X = all the other features.

In [135]:
sec_c_trainX = sect_c_train.drop(['vote_turnouts'],axis=1,inplace=False)
sec_c_trainY = sect_c_train['vote_turnouts']
sec_c_testX = sect_c_test.drop(['vote_turnouts'],axis=1,inplace=False)
sec_c_testY = sect_c_test['vote_turnouts']

In [139]:
states = ['CALIFORNIA','FLORIDA','SOUTH DAKOTA','WYOMING']

print("Majority party for each state per year")

for s in states:
    print(s," : ",votes_turnouts_df.loc[votes_turnouts_df['state'] == s]['party'].values)

Majority party for each state per year
CALIFORNIA  :  ['D' 'D' 'D' 'D' 'D' 'D']
FLORIDA  :  ['R' 'R' 'R' 'R' 'R' 'R']
SOUTH DAKOTA  :  ['R' 'D' 'D' 'D' 'D' 'R']
WYOMING  :  ['R' 'R' 'R' 'R' 'R' 'R']

It can be seen that in Florida, Wyoming and California there has been a clear decision for Republicans or Democrats respectively over the years. In contrast, in the state South Dakota there has been a change in the dominant party over the Observed years. We assume that these findings and the connection between them can be explained by the level of political involvement of the citizens. In countries where the decision is clear and known in advance we assume that as a result many citizens did not go out to vote and therefore the turnout was low. On the other hand, in countries where the political struggle has changed over the years, we assume that the political involvement of the citizens is high and their desire to vote and influence is expressed in a higher turnout. In addition, our assumption is supported by the investigation of the difference in votes that the party has received over the years in these countries.

As we can see in most cases the state majority party in the House elections is also the same party in the Senate
and the presidential elections
. The presidential elections indicator does not seems to be a good indicator of the majority party.

Estimate population and eligible voters in the missing years

In [175]:
#estimate population
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(pop2018=lambda x: x['pop2017']* x['pop_groth_per'])
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(pop2020=lambda x: x['pop2018']* x['pop_groth_per']**2)
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(pop2022=lambda x: x['pop2020']* x['pop_groth_per']**2)

#estimate eligible voters
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(eligible_voters_2000=lambda x: (x['pop2000'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(eligible_voters_2014=lambda x: (x['pop2014'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(eligible_voters_2016=lambda x: (x['pop2016'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(eligible_voters_2018=lambda x: (x['pop2018'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(eligible_voters_2020=lambda x: (x['pop2020'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)
general_demog_df_sec_e = general_demog_df_sec_e.assign(eligible_voters_2022=lambda x: (x['pop2022'] * (100-x['age_under_18_2010']))/100)

#selecting relevant features for estimating eligible_voters
section_e_df = general_demog_df_sec_e[['fips','state','eligible_voters_2000', 'eligible_voters_2002', 'eligible_voters_2004', 'eligible_voters_2006', 'eligible_voters_2008', 'eligible_voters_2010','eligible_voters_2012','eligible_voters_2014','eligible_voters_2016','eligible_voters_2018','eligible_voters_2020','eligible_voters_2022']]
#grouping counties by state
section_e_df_groupedby = section_e_df.groupby(['state'])

section_e_df_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#estimating eligible_voters for 2000-2012
for key,item in section_e_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state = section_e_df_groupedby.get_group(key)
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2000'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2000'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2002'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2002'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2004'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2004'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2006'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2006'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2008'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2008'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2010'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2010'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2012'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2012'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2014'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2014'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2016'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2016'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2018'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2018'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2020'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2020'].sum()
    counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2022'] = counties_per_state['eligible_voters_2022'].sum()
    section_e_df_after_arrange = section_e_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state.iloc[0:1,1:])

In [185]:
#grouping counties by state and year
house_section_e_df_groupedby = merged_section_e.groupby(['state','year'])

house_section_e_df_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#estimating vote turnouts and D/R class for each state for 2000-2020
for key,item in house_section_e_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state_per_year = item
    #getting the matched eligible_voters column name
    column_name = return_column_name(key[1])

    #calc vote turnout
    counties_per_state_per_year['vote_turnouts'] = counties_per_state_per_year['candidatevotes'].sum()/counties_per_state_per_year[column_name].iloc[:1].values[0]

    #calc Republican votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party'] == 'REPUBLICAN']['candidatevotes'].sum()
    #calc Democrats votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party'] == 'DEMOCRAT']['candidatevotes'].sum()

    # classify state as D or R based on total votes of each party
    if counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0] >= counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0]:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party'] = 'D'
    else:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party'] = 'R'

    num_of_counties = len(counties_per_state_per_year)
    #calc the amount of special = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['special'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['special'] == 1]['special'])/num_of_counties
    #calc the amount of writein = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] == 1]['writein'])/num_of_counties

    #add row to the arranged df
    house_section_e_df_after_arrange = house_section_e_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state_per_year.iloc[0:1,:])

#estimating vote turnouts and D/R class for each state for 2000-2020
for key,item in merged_president_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state_per_year = item
    #getting the matched eligible_voters column name
    column_name = return_column_name(key[1])

    #calc vote turnout
    counties_per_state_per_year['vote_turnouts'] = counties_per_state_per_year['candidatevotes'].sum()/counties_per_state_per_year[column_name].iloc[:1].values[0]

    #calc Republican votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'REPUBLICAN']['candidatevotes'].sum()
    #calc Democrats votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'DEMOCRAT']['candidatevotes'].sum()

    # classify state as D or R based on total votes of each party
    if counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0] >= counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0]:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] = 'D'
    else:
        counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] = 'R'

    num_of_counties = len(counties_per_state_per_year)
    #calc the amount of writein = 1
    counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] = len(counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['writein'] == 1]['writein'])/num_of_counties

    #add row to the arranged df
    merged_president_df_after_arrange = merged_president_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state_per_year.iloc[0:1,:])

    #calc Republican votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'REPUBLICAN']['candidatevotes'].sum()
    #calc Democrats votes
    counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'] = counties_per_state_per_year.loc[counties_per_state_per_year['party_simplified'] == 'DEMOCRAT']['candidatevotes'].sum()

    # classify state as D or R based on total votes of each party
    if counties_per_state_per_year['Democrats_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0] >= counties_per_state_per_year['Republican_votes'].iloc[:1].values[0]:

      dtype='object')

Creating samples for 2022 predictions

Our elections' data contains data from 1976-2020 elections.
Our task is to predict the majority party in each state in the Senate 2022 elections.
For that we need to create samples that present the states in the 2022 elections, therefor we will estimate values
for our X features by using statistical estimators like(mean, median, mode etc.).

In [222]:
#grouping counties by state and year
merged_e_df_groupedby = section_e_finale_df.groupby(['state'])
categorical_list = ['party','party_president','party_senate']
numeric_list = ['special_x','writein','vote_turnouts','writein_president','vote_turnouts_president','special_y','writein_senate','vote_turnouts_senate']
merged_states_df_2022 = pd.DataFrame()
for key,item in merged_e_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state = item
    state_2022 = {}

    for feature in counties_per_state.columns:
        if feature =='year':
            state_2022['year']=2022
        elif feature =='state':
            state_2022['state']=key
        elif feature in categorical_list:
            state_2022[feature]=stats.mode(counties_per_state[feature].values)[0]
        elif feature in numeric_list:
            state_2022[feature]=np.percentile(counties_per_state[feature].values,50)
        else:
            state_2022[feature]=counties_per_state[feature].iloc[0:1]
    #add row to the arranged df
    merged_states_df_2022 = merged_states_df_2022.append(pd.DataFrame.from_dict(state_2022))

PCA Algorithm

We chose to perform a PCA in order to lower the dimensions.
We will select the 2 PCs that take up most of the overall variance of the data.
Our goal is to represent the data in 2 dimensions and see how it is divided into clusters.

Goodness of the clusters by silhouette coefficient

Explanation of the method

Our goal is that in a well-formed set of clusters are as follows:
-The observations within a cluster to be as close as possible. This is referred to as Cohesion.
-The observations from two clusters should be far from each other. This is referred to as Separation.
We can evaluate those by using Silhouette coefficient,
which is a method that uses the concept of both cohesion and separation.
The calculation goes as follows:
For each point i in a cluster j:

  1. We calculate the distance of the point i from all the points in j and find the average, this is called $\large a_i$
    of point i(our cohesion measurement).

  2. For another cluster k we calculate the distance of the point i from all the points in k and find the average,
    we do it for each other cluster beside k, the minimum of all those averages distances is chosen and called
    $\large b_i$(our separation measurement).

  3. Then Silhouette coefficient for the point i is:

    $\large S_i = (b_i - a_i)/max(a_i, b_i).$

For a cluster the Silhouette coefficient needs to be calculated for all the points, the average is taken.
The value lies between -1 and 1, higher the value better is the cluster.
For more explanation, example of Silhouette coefficient and other evaluation methods click here.

In [246]:
#calculate and return the euclidean distance of 2 data points
def euclidean_distance(x,y):
    dist_arr = []#array for storing squared distance  in each dimension
    for feature in x.columns:
        if feature != 'State':
            #squared distance in specific dimension
           dist_arr.append(((y[feature] - x[feature])**2))
    #summing the squared distances and apply square root
    return np.sqrt(np.sum(dist_arr))
In [247]:
#calculate distances of specific point in a cluster from all the other points in the same cluster
# or other cluster. then calculate and return the average of those distances
def distance_within_or_outside(point_i,cluster):
    euc_dist_arr = []#array for storing euclidean distance  of point_i from all other points in the same cluster, or another one
    for i,point in cluster.iterrows():
        #calculating the euclidean distance of point_i and another point
        dist = euclidean_distance(point_i,point)
        #prevent from adding the distance from itself
        if dist != 0:
            euc_dist_arr.append(dist)
    #calculating the average distance
    return np.sum(euc_dist_arr)/(len(euc_dist_arr))
In [248]:
#calculate the average distance of specific point from all the other clusters and return the minimum(bi)
def calc_bi(point_i,clusters):
    min_bi = float('inf')
    for cluster in clusters:
        bi = distance_within_or_outside(point_i,cluster)
        if bi < min_bi:
            min_bi = bi
    return min_bi
In [249]:
#calucate Silhouette coefficient of specific point i
def silhouette_coefficient_point_i(a_i, b_i):
    return (b_i - a_i)/np.maximum(a_i, b_i)
In [250]:
#calucate the average Silhouette coefficient of a specific cluster
def silhouette_coefficient(df,cluster_i,clusters):
    #storing the ai values(cohesion) of each sample in cluster i
    ai_array = []
    #storing the bi values(separation)of  each sample in cluster i
    bi_array = []
    #storing the silhouette coefficients (separation+cohesion)of  each sample in cluster i
    silhouette_coefficients_array = []
    #calculate ai and bi for cluster_i samples
    for point_i in cluster_i.index:
        #calculate bi for cluster_i samples
        bi_array.append(calc_bi(df.iloc[point_i:point_i+1],clusters))
        #calculate ai for cluster_i samples
        ai_array.append(distance_within_or_outside(df.iloc[point_i:point_i+1],cluster_i))

    #calculate Silhouette coefficient for cluster_i samples
    for i in range(0,len(ai_array)):
        silhouette_coefficients_array.append(silhouette_coefficient_point_i(ai_array[i], bi_array[i]))
    #calucate the average Silhouette coefficient of  cluster_i
    return np.mean(silhouette_coefficients_array)

Gradiant Boost

In [255]:
def g_boost(train_x, train_y, test_x, test_y):
    # define model
    gb = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=RSEED)

    # define parameter grid
    parameters_grid = {
        'learning_rate': [0.5,0.75, 1, 1.5],
        'n_estimators': [30, 60, 100,150,200],
    }

    # define grid search
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=gb, param_grid=parameters_grid, cv=10)

    start_time = time.time()
    # fit estimator
    grid_search.fit(train_x, train_y)
    print("sklearn gradiant boost fit time %s seconds ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

    # get best estimator
    best = grid_search.best_estimator_

    # print best parameters
    print(pd.DataFrame.from_dict(grid_search.best_params_, orient='index', columns=['Selected Value']).T)

    # predict
    y_pred = best.predict(test_x)

    MSE = round(mean_squared_error(test_y, y_pred), 3)
    R2 = r2_score(test_y, y_pred)
    pd.set_option('display.float_format', lambda x: '%.3f' % x)
    df = pd.DataFrame([MSE, R2]).T
    df = df.rename(index={0: 'Gradiant Boost Regressor'}, columns={0: 'MSE', 1: 'R^2'})
    print(df)
    return MSE, R2, grid_search, y_pred

Random Forest

In [268]:
def r_forest(train_x, train_y, test_x, test_y):
    rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=RSEED)

    # define parameter grid
    parameters_grid = {
        'max_depth': [5,8],
        'min_samples_split': [3,5,10,15, 30],
        'n_estimators': [20, 50,70]
    }

    # define grid search
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=rf, param_grid=parameters_grid, cv=10)

    # fit estimator
    start_time = time.time()
    grid_search.fit(train_x, train_y)
    print("sklearn gradiant boost fit time %s seconds ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

    # get best estimator
    best = grid_search.best_estimator_

    # print best parameters
    print(pd.DataFrame.from_dict(grid_search.best_params_, orient='index', columns=['Selected Value']).T)

    # predict
    y_pred = best.predict(test_x)

    MSE = round(mean_squared_error(test_y, y_pred), 3)
    R2 = r2_score(test_y, y_pred)
    pd.set_option('display.float_format', lambda x: '%.3f' % x)
    df = pd.DataFrame([MSE, R2]).T
    df = df.rename(index={0: 'Random Forest Regressor'}, columns={0: 'MSE', 1: 'R^2'})
    print(df)
    return MSE, R2, grid_search, y_pred

Adaboot

In [280]:
def ada_boost(train_x, train_y, test_x, test_y):
    # define model
    ab = AdaBoostRegressor(random_state=RSEED)

    # define parameter grid
    parameters_grid = {
        'n_estimators': [50,70]
    }

    # define grid search
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=ab, param_grid=parameters_grid, cv=10)
    # fit estimator
    start_time = time.time()
    grid_search.fit(train_x, train_y)
    print("sklearn Ada boost fit time %s seconds ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

    # get best estimator
    best = grid_search.best_estimator_

    # print best parameters
    print(pd.DataFrame.from_dict(grid_search.best_params_, orient='index', columns=['Selected Value']).T)

    # predict
    y_pred = best.predict(test_x)


    MSE = round(mean_squared_error(test_y,  y_pred), 3)
    R2 = r2_score(test_y,   y_pred)
    pd.set_option('display.float_format', lambda x: '%.3f' % x)
    df = pd.DataFrame([MSE, R2]).T
    df = df.rename(index={0: 'AdaBoost Regressor'}, columns={0: 'MSE', 1: 'R^2'})
    print(df)
    return MSE, R2, grid_search,   y_pred

Adding predicted values column

In [290]:
sec_c_test_improvement = sec_c_improvment.loc[sec_c_improvment['year']>=2010]
#Add predicted values column

Grouping by states and calculating SSR.

In [291]:
#grouping counties by state
sec_c_improvment_groupedby = sec_c_test_improvement.groupby(['state'])

sec_c_improvment_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
for key,item in sec_c_improvment_groupedby:
    state_samples = item
    state_samples = state_samples.assign(SSR=lambda x: (x['predicted vals'] - x['vote_turnouts'])**2)
    state_samples['SSR'] = np.sum(state_samples['SSR'])
    sec_c_improvment_after_arrange = sec_c_improvment_after_arrange.append(state_samples.iloc[0:1,:])
In [292]:
c_improvment_after_arrange = sec_c_improvment_after_arrange[['state', 'SSR']]

Checking for outliers in the best predictors

As we saw earlier the Senate turn vote turnouts feature has high correlation of 0.8
with our target(House turn vote outs).
Also, the Presidential turn vote outs has relative high correlation of 0.7 with our target.
if there are any outliers in those features this can harm the predictions of our model.
Therefor lets check for any outliers if there are any we will change their values to
the 10 percentile or the 90 percentile, considering the outlier direction.

Vote turnouts senate

In [295]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
ax = sns.boxplot(x=sec_c_improvment['vote_turnouts_senate'])

As we can see we have 6 outliers, lets print them.

In [296]:
#IQR(0.75percentile - 0.25percentile)
IQR = np.percentile(sec_c_improvment['vote_turnouts_senate'],75) - np.percentile(sec_c_improvment['vote_turnouts_senate'],25)
#lower and upper bounds(any samples beyond are outliers)
upper = np.percentile(sec_c_improvment['vote_turnouts_senate'],75)+1.5*IQR
lower = np.percentile(sec_c_improvment['vote_turnouts_senate'],25)-1.5*IQR
senate_outliers = sec_c_improvment.loc[(sec_c_improvment['vote_turnouts_senate'] > upper) | (sec_c_improvment['vote_turnouts_senate'] < lower)][['year','state','vote_turnouts','vote_turnouts_senate']]

As we can see the differences in 2010 at those states are extremely higher,
in Virginia and Louisiana there are the lowest and also very similar.
Therefore we will try to improve the predictions of those two states.

Over sampling

As we saw above in the 5 states with the worst predictions something abnormal happens in 2010.
Although Senate vote turnouts feature has high correlation of 0.8
with our target, in 2010
there is a high difference between the values of the House turn outs and the senate turn outs,
which is the feature our models uses the most for the predicting, and therefore the predictions results for
those states are the worst.
Let's try duplicates samples with the same values of 2010 for Louisiana and Virginia and add them to our training
dataframe so our model will be trained also on the abnormal samples, and therefore hopefully will produce
better results for those states.

In [309]:
over_sampling_df=sec_c_improvment.copy(deep = True)
In [310]:
two_States_anomalies = sec_c_improvment.loc[(sec_c_improvment['year'] == 2010)&((sec_c_improvment['state'] == 'VIRGINIA') | (sec_c_improvment['state'] == 'LOUISIANA'))]
two_States_anomalies.drop('year',axis=1,inplace = False)

#seperte the data to train and test
sec_c_imp_train = over_sampling_df.loc[over_sampling_df['year'] < 2010]
sec_c_imp_test = over_sampling_df.loc[over_sampling_df['year'] >= 2010]

#define train dataset
sec_c_trainX = sec_c_imp_train.drop('vote_turnouts', inplace=False, axis=1)
sec_c_trainY = sec_c_imp_train['vote_turnouts']

#define test dataset
sec_c_testX = sec_c_imp_test.drop('vote_turnouts', inplace=False, axis=1)
states = sec_c_testX['state']
sec_c_testY = sec_c_imp_test['vote_turnouts']

#encoding categorical features
sec_c_trainX = encoding_features(sec_c_trainX, ['state', 'party'])
sec_c_testX = encoding_features(sec_c_testX, ['state', 'party'])

#running the adaboost mode;
ada_MSE, ada_R2, ada_gridsearch, Adaboost_predicted_vals = ada_boost(sec_c_trainX, sec_c_trainY, sec_c_testX,
                                                                     sec_c_testY)

As we can see we managed to overall improve the results of our model,

Let's see if we also managed to improve Virginia and Louisiana predictions in a way that now they will be among
the top 25.

In [315]:
test = sec_c_imp_test.copy(deep=True)
#add predicted values column
test['predicted vals'] = Adaboost_predicted_vals
test
#grouping data by state
groupedby = test.groupby(['state'])

test_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#calculating SSR for each state
for key, item in groupedby:
    state_samples = item
    state_samples = state_samples.assign(SSR=lambda x: (x['predicted vals'] - x['vote_turnouts']) ** 2)
    #summing the Squared error of each state of for both years
    state_samples['SSR'] = np.sum(state_samples['SSR'])
    test_after_arrange = test_after_arrange.append(state_samples.iloc[0:1, :])

Section D - (Classification) house majority party predictions

Task

Use the total votes counted by state in house elections cycle to create
the label. If more votes were given to the democrat candidates in total, the state should be classified as D.
Otherwise, if more votes were given to the republican candidates, the state should be categorized as R.
Predict house majaority party in the 2010 and 2012 elections

Checking different Models

Classification Tree

In [318]:
##sclearn implementation
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=RSEED)
# define parameter grid
parameters_grid = {
    'max_depth': [2,4],
    'min_samples_leaf': [2,4,6,8,15,20],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 4, 8,30],
}

# define grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt, param_grid=parameters_grid, cv=10)

# fit estimator
start_time = time.time()
grid_search.fit(sec_d_trainX, sec_d_trainY)
print("building classify tree ended in %s seconds" % (time.time() - start_time))
# get best estimator
best = grid_search.best_estimator_

# print best parameters
print(pd.DataFrame.from_dict(grid_search.best_params_, orient='index', columns=['Selected Value']).T)
# predict
y_pred = best.predict(sec_d_testX)

#evaluating
# calculate accuracy
acc = round(accuracy_score(sec_d_testY, y_pred), 3)

df = pd.DataFrame([acc]).T
df = df.rename(index={0: 'Decision Tree Classifier'}, columns={0: 'Accuracy'})
df
print(df)

#confusion_matrix
plot_confusion_matrix(grid_search, sec_d_testX , sec_d_testY)
plt.show()

tp, fn, fp, tn = confusion_matrix(sec_d_testY, y_pred).ravel()
eval_Df = {"sensitivity": tp/(tp+fn), "specificity": tn/(tn+fp)}
pd.DataFrame(data=eval_Df, index=[0])

Summery

As we can see the Neural Network got the best accuracy score(0.86) after it
is the KNN(0.84), and third are Gradient Boost along with the SVM(0.81), the most important feature in building the Gradient boost was:
-party_Senate(the majority party in particular state in specific year in the Senate election).
As, we saw that there is a pattern between the dominated parties in this elections and in the
House elections.

test_sensitivity, test_specificity = get_metrics(mlp, sec_e_2022Y, predict_2022)

df = pd.DataFrame([test_acc, test_sensitivity, test_specificity]).T
df = df.rename(index={0: 'MLPClassifier 2022 Senate elections:'}, columns={0: 'Accuracy', 1: 'Sensitivity', 2: 'Specificity'})
print(df)

                                      Accuracy  Sensitivity  Specificity
MLPClassifier 2022 Senate elections:     0.970        1.000        0.952
In [344]:
plot_confusion_matrix(mlp, X_scaled_2022, sec_e_2022Y)
plt.show()

Summery

Our Neural network predicted the estimated results with accuracy of 97%, and actual past results with accuracy of 91.8%
Near to the elections in November when the required X features will be available, another more accurate predicting
will be possible to apply.
Now lets see that will be the parties ratio after the elections according to the model.

In [350]:
#grouping counties by state
merged_senate2020_df_groupedby = senate_2020_df.groupby(['state'])

merged_senate2020_df_after_arrange = pd.DataFrame()
#caluctaing the number of Republicans and Democrats representatives in each state today
for key,item in merged_senate2020_df_groupedby:
    counties_per_state = item
    counties_per_state['R'] = len(counties_per_state.loc[counties_per_state['party'] == 'Republican'])
    counties_per_state['D'] = len(counties_per_state.loc[(counties_per_state['party'] == 'Democratic') | (counties_per_state['party'] == 'Independent')])
    merged_senate2020_df_after_arrange = merged_senate2020_df_after_arrange.append(counties_per_state.iloc[0:1,:])
merged_senate2020_df_after_arrange.drop('party',axis=1,inplace=True)

#calculating the representatives status after the results in the relevant states
for i in range(0,33):
    if relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['Majority_party'] == 'R' and relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['R'] < 2:
        relevant_states_senate_2022.iat[i,1] = relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['R'] + 1
        relevant_states_senate_2022.iat[i,2] = relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['D'] - 1
    elif relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['Majority_party'] == 'D' and relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['D'] < 2:
        relevant_states_senate_2022.iat[i,1] = relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['R'] - 1
        relevant_states_senate_2022.iat[i,2] = relevant_states_senate_2022.iloc[i]['D'] + 1
relevant_states_senate_2022

Outcome

After adding the senate representatives from states that don't participate in the elections(21 D, 13 R)
we get that in total the Democrats will get 48 representatives and the Republicans 52,
which means that the tie will be broken!
